  <h2 class="section-heading" id="graphs"><span class="section-icon">G</span> Graphs</h2>

  <div class="problem-card"><div class="problem-card-header"><span class="problem-number">#133</span><h3 class="problem-heading" style="margin:0">Clone Graph</h3><span class="tag tag-orange">Medium</span></div><div class="problem-card-body"><div class="technique-row"><span class="technique-label">🎯 Technique</span><span class="tag tag-blue">DFS + HashMap</span><span class="tag tag-purple">Graph Deep Copy with Cycle Handling</span></div><div class="panel info"><span class="panel-icon">💡</span><div class="panel-content"><strong>Approach — DFS with Visited Map</strong>Map original nodes to their clones. Before recursing into a neighbor, check if it's already cloned (prevents infinite loops in cyclic graphs). DFS naturally handles both the node creation and edge reconstruction.</div></div><table class="complexity-table"><thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th>Complexity</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Time</td><td class="complexity-time">O(V+E)</td><td>Visit every node and edge once</td></tr><tr><td>Space</td><td class="complexity-space">O(V)</td><td>HashMap + recursion stack</td></tr></tbody></table><div class="code-block"><div class="code-header"><span class="code-lang">Java</span></div><pre><span class="kw">class</span> <span class="tp">Solution</span> {
    <span class="tp">Map</span>&lt;<span class="tp">Node</span>,<span class="tp">Node</span>&gt; visited=<span class="kw">new</span> <span class="tp">HashMap</span>&lt;&gt;();
    <span class="kw">public</span> <span class="tp">Node</span> <span class="fn">cloneGraph</span>(<span class="tp">Node</span> node){
        <span class="kw">if</span>(node==<span class="kw">null</span>)<span class="kw">return null</span>;
        <span class="kw">if</span>(visited.containsKey(node) {
                )<span class="kw">return</span> visited.get(node);
            }
        <span class="tp">Node</span> clone=<span class="kw">new</span> <span class="tp">Node</span>(node.val);
        visited.put(node,clone);
        <span class="kw">for</span>(<span class="tp">Node</span> n:node.neighbors) clone.neighbors.add(<span class="fn">cloneGraph</span>(n));
        <span class="kw">return</span> clone;
    }
}</pre></div></div></div>

  <div class="problem-card"><div class="problem-card-header"><span class="problem-number">#200</span><h3 class="problem-heading" style="margin:0">Number of Islands</h3><span class="tag tag-orange">Medium</span></div><div class="problem-card-body"><div class="technique-row"><span class="technique-label">🎯 Technique</span><span class="tag tag-blue">DFS Flood Fill</span><span class="tag tag-purple">Connected Components</span></div><div class="panel info"><span class="panel-icon">💡</span><div class="panel-content"><strong>Approach — DFS Flood Fill</strong>For each unvisited '1', launch a DFS that marks all connected land as visited (sink it to '0'). Each DFS call equals one new island. Classic connected-components counting via DFS flood fill.</div></div><table class="complexity-table"><thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th>Complexity</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Time</td><td class="complexity-time">O(m × n)</td><td>Each cell processed once</td></tr><tr><td>Space</td><td class="complexity-space">O(m × n)</td><td>DFS recursion stack</td></tr></tbody></table><div class="code-block"><div class="code-header"><span class="code-lang">Java</span></div><pre><span class="kw">class</span> <span class="tp">Solution</span> {
    <span class="kw">public int</span> <span class="fn">numIslands</span>(<span class="kw">char</span>[][] g){
        <span class="kw">int</span> cnt=<span class="nm">0</span>;
        <span class="kw">for</span>(<span class="kw">int</span> i=<span class="nm">0</span>;i&lt;g.length;i++) <span class="kw">for</span>(<span class="kw">int</span> j=<span class="nm">0</span>;j&lt;g[<span class="nm">0</span>].length;j++)
            <span class="kw">if</span>(g[i][j]==<span class="st">'1'</span>){<span class="fn">dfs</span>(g,i,j);cnt++;}
        <span class="kw">return</span> cnt;
    }
    <span class="kw">void</span> <span class="fn">dfs</span>(<span class="kw">char</span>[][] g,<span class="kw">int</span> i,<span class="kw">int</span> j){
        <span class="kw">if</span>(i&lt;<span class="nm">0</span>||i&gt;=g.length||j&lt;<span class="nm">0</span>||j&gt;=g[<span class="nm">0</span>].length||g[i][j]!=<span class="st">'1'</span>)<span class="kw">return</span>;
        g[i][j]=<span class="st">'0'</span>;
        <span class="fn">dfs</span>(g,i+<span class="nm">1</span>,j);<span class="fn">dfs</span>(g,i-<span class="nm">1</span>,j);<span class="fn">dfs</span>(g,i,j+<span class="nm">1</span>);<span class="fn">dfs</span>(g,i,j-<span class="nm">1</span>);
    }
}</pre></div></div></div>

  <div class="problem-card"><div class="problem-card-header"><span class="problem-number">#207</span><h3 class="problem-heading" style="margin:0">Course Schedule</h3><span class="tag tag-orange">Medium</span></div><div class="problem-card-body"><div class="technique-row"><span class="technique-label">🎯 Technique</span><span class="tag tag-blue">Topological Sort</span><span class="tag tag-purple">DFS Cycle Detection (3-Color)</span></div><div class="panel info"><span class="panel-icon">💡</span><div class="panel-content"><strong>Approach — 3-State DFS (White/Gray/Black)</strong>Nodes have states: 0=unvisited, 1=in current path (gray), 2=fully processed (black). If DFS visits a gray node, a cycle exists. No cycle → all courses can be finished.</div></div><table class="complexity-table"><thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th>Complexity</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Time</td><td class="complexity-time">O(V+E)</td><td>Visit all nodes and edges</td></tr><tr><td>Space</td><td class="complexity-space">O(V+E)</td><td>Adjacency list + state array</td></tr></tbody></table><div class="code-block"><div class="code-header"><span class="code-lang">Java</span></div><pre><span class="kw">class</span> <span class="tp">Solution</span> {
    <span class="kw">public boolean</span> <span class="fn">canFinish</span>(<span class="kw">int</span> n,<span class="kw">int</span>[][] pre){
        <span class="tp">List</span>&lt;<span class="tp">List</span>&lt;<span class="tp">Integer</span>&gt;&gt; g=<span class="kw">new</span> <span class="tp">ArrayList</span>&lt;&gt;();
        <span class="kw">for</span>(<span class="kw">int</span> i=<span class="nm">0</span>;i&lt;n;i++)g.add(<span class="kw">new</span> <span class="tp">ArrayList</span>&lt;&gt;());
        <span class="kw">for</span>(<span class="kw">int</span>[] p:pre)g.get(p[<span class="nm">1</span>]).add(p[<span class="nm">0</span>]);
        <span class="kw">int</span>[] state=<span class="kw">new int</span>[n];
        <span class="kw">for</span>(<span class="kw">int</span> i=<span class="nm">0</span>;i&lt;n;i++) <span class="kw">if</span>(<span class="fn">cycle</span>(g,state,i) {
                )<span class="kw">return false</span>;
            }
        <span class="kw">return true</span>;
    }
    <span class="kw">boolean</span> <span class="fn">cycle</span>(<span class="tp">List</span>&lt;<span class="tp">List</span>&lt;<span class="tp">Integer</span>&gt;&gt; g,<span class="kw">int</span>[] st,<span class="kw">int</span> v){
        <span class="kw">if</span>(st[v]==<span class="nm">1</span>)<span class="kw">return true</span>; <span class="kw">if</span>(st[v]==<span class="nm">2</span>)<span class="kw">return false</span>;
        st[v]=<span class="nm">1</span>;
        <span class="kw">for</span>(<span class="kw">int</span> nb:g.get(v)) <span class="kw">if</span>(<span class="fn">cycle</span>(g,st,nb) {
                )<span class="kw">return true</span>;
            }
        st[v]=<span class="nm">2</span>; <span class="kw">return false</span>;
    }
}</pre></div></div></div>

  <div class="problem-card"><div class="problem-card-header"><span class="problem-number">#785</span><h3 class="problem-heading" style="margin:0">Is Graph Bipartite?</h3><span class="tag tag-orange">Medium</span></div><div class="problem-card-body"><div class="technique-row"><span class="technique-label">🎯 Technique</span><span class="tag tag-blue">BFS Graph Coloring</span><span class="tag tag-purple">2-Coloring</span></div><div class="panel info"><span class="panel-icon">💡</span><div class="panel-content"><strong>Approach — BFS 2-Coloring</strong>Attempt to color the graph with 2 colors such that no two adjacent nodes share the same color. If a conflict is found during BFS, the graph is not bipartite. Handle disconnected components with an outer loop.</div></div><table class="complexity-table"><thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th>Complexity</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Time</td><td class="complexity-time">O(V+E)</td><td>BFS visits all nodes and edges</td></tr><tr><td>Space</td><td class="complexity-space">O(V)</td><td>Color array + queue</td></tr></tbody></table><div class="code-block"><div class="code-header"><span class="code-lang">Java</span></div><pre><span class="kw">class</span> <span class="tp">Solution</span> {
    <span class="kw">public boolean</span> <span class="fn">isBipartite</span>(<span class="kw">int</span>[][] g){
        <span class="kw">int</span>[] color=<span class="kw">new int</span>[g.length]; <span class="tp">Arrays</span>.fill(color,-<span class="nm">1</span>);
        <span class="kw">for</span>(<span class="kw">int</span> i=<span class="nm">0</span>;i&lt;g.length;i++){
            <span class="kw">if</span>(color[i]!=-<span class="nm">1</span>)<span class="kw">continue</span>;
            <span class="tp">Queue</span>&lt;<span class="tp">Integer</span>&gt; q=<span class="kw">new</span> <span class="tp">LinkedList</span>&lt;&gt;(); q.offer(i);color[i]=<span class="nm">0</span>;
            <span class="kw">while</span>(!q.isEmpty()){
                <span class="kw">int</span> node=q.poll();
                <span class="kw">for</span>(<span class="kw">int</span> nb:g[node]){
                    <span class="kw">if</span>(color[nb]==-<span class="nm">1</span>){color[nb]=<span class="nm">1</span>-color[node];q.offer(nb);}
                    <span class="kw">else if</span>(color[nb]==color[node])<span class="kw">return false</span>;
                }
            }
        }
        <span class="kw">return true</span>;
    }
}</pre></div></div></div>

  <div class="problem-card"><div class="problem-card-header"><span class="problem-number">#994</span><h3 class="problem-heading" style="margin:0">Rotting Oranges</h3><span class="tag tag-orange">Medium</span></div><div class="problem-card-body"><div class="technique-row"><span class="technique-label">🎯 Technique</span><span class="tag tag-blue">Multi-Source BFS</span><span class="tag tag-purple">Simultaneous Spread Simulation</span></div><div class="panel info"><span class="panel-icon">💡</span><div class="panel-content"><strong>Approach — Multi-Source BFS (Level = 1 Minute)</strong>Seed the BFS queue with all initially rotten oranges. Spread rot layer-by-layer (each BFS level = 1 minute). Count remaining fresh oranges. If any remain after BFS completes, return -1.</div></div><table class="complexity-table"><thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th>Complexity</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Time</td><td class="complexity-time">O(m × n)</td><td>Visit every cell at most once</td></tr><tr><td>Space</td><td class="complexity-space">O(m × n)</td><td>BFS queue</td></tr></tbody></table><div class="code-block"><div class="code-header"><span class="code-lang">Java</span></div><pre><span class="kw">class</span> <span class="tp">Solution</span> {
    <span class="kw">public int</span> <span class="fn">orangesRotting</span>(<span class="kw">int</span>[][] g){
        <span class="kw">int</span> rows=g.length,cols=g[<span class="nm">0</span>].length,fresh=<span class="nm">0</span>,mins=<span class="nm">0</span>;
        <span class="tp">Queue</span>&lt;<span class="kw">int</span>[]&gt; q=<span class="kw">new</span> <span class="tp">LinkedList</span>&lt;&gt;();
        <span class="kw">for</span>(<span class="kw">int</span> i=<span class="nm">0</span>;i&lt;rows;i++) <span class="kw">for</span>(<span class="kw">int</span> j=<span class="nm">0</span>;j&lt;cols;j++){
            <span class="kw">if</span>(g[i][j]==<span class="nm">2</span>) {
                q.offer(<span class="kw">new int</span>[]{i,j});
            }
            <span class="kw">else if</span>(g[i][j]==<span class="nm">1</span>) {
                fresh++;
            }
        }
        <span class="kw">int</span>[][] dirs={{<span class="nm">1</span>,<span class="nm">0</span>},{-<span class="nm">1</span>,<span class="nm">0</span>},{<span class="nm">0</span>,<span class="nm">1</span>},{<span class="nm">0</span>,-<span class="nm">1</span>}};
        <span class="kw">while</span>(!q.isEmpty()&amp;&amp;fresh&gt;<span class="nm">0</span>){
            mins++;
            <span class="kw">for</span>(<span class="kw">int</span> k=q.size();k&gt;<span class="nm">0</span>;k--){
                <span class="kw">int</span>[] c=q.poll();
                <span class="kw">for</span>(<span class="kw">int</span>[] d:dirs){
                    <span class="kw">int</span> r=c[<span class="nm">0</span>]+d[<span class="nm">0</span>],col=c[<span class="nm">1</span>]+d[<span class="nm">1</span>];
                    <span class="kw">if</span>(r&gt;=<span class="nm">0</span>&amp;&amp;r&lt;rows&amp;&amp;col&gt;=<span class="nm">0</span>&amp;&amp;col&lt;cols&amp;&amp;g[r][col]==<span class="nm">1</span>){
                        g[r][col]=<span class="nm">2</span>;fresh--;q.offer(<span class="kw">new int</span>[]{r,col});
                    }
                }
            }
        }
        <span class="kw">return</span> fresh==<span class="nm">0</span>?mins:-<span class="nm">1</span>;
    }
}</pre></div></div></div>

  <div class="problem-card"><div class="problem-card-header"><span class="problem-number">#323</span><h3 class="problem-heading" style="margin:0">Number of Connected Components</h3><span class="tag tag-orange">Medium</span></div><div class="problem-card-body"><div class="technique-row"><span class="technique-label">🎯 Technique</span><span class="tag tag-blue">Union-Find (DSU)</span><span class="tag tag-purple">Path Compression + Rank</span></div><div class="panel info"><span class="panel-icon">💡</span><div class="panel-content"><strong>Approach — Union-Find (Disjoint Set Union)</strong>Each node starts as its own root. For each edge, union the two nodes. If they already share a root, no new component created. Otherwise, decrement component count. Path compression makes find() nearly O(1).</div></div><table class="complexity-table"><thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th>Complexity</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Time</td><td class="complexity-time">O(n + E·α(n))</td><td>α ≈ O(1) with path compression</td></tr><tr><td>Space</td><td class="complexity-space">O(n)</td><td>Parent array</td></tr></tbody></table><div class="code-block"><div class="code-header"><span class="code-lang">Java</span></div><pre><span class="kw">class</span> <span class="tp">Solution</span> {
    <span class="kw">int</span>[] parent;
    <span class="kw">public int</span> <span class="fn">countComponents</span>(<span class="kw">int</span> n,<span class="kw">int</span>[][] edges){
        parent=<span class="kw">new int</span>[n]; <span class="kw">for</span>(<span class="kw">int</span> i=<span class="nm">0</span>;i&lt;n;i++)parent[i]=i;
        <span class="kw">int</span> comp=n;
        <span class="kw">for</span>(<span class="kw">int</span>[] e:edges){
            <span class="kw">int</span> p1=<span class="fn">find</span>(e[<span class="nm">0</span>]),p2=<span class="fn">find</span>(e[<span class="nm">1</span>]);
            <span class="kw">if</span>(p1!=p2){parent[p1]=p2;comp--;}
        }
        <span class="kw">return</span> comp;
    }
    <span class="kw">int</span> <span class="fn">find</span>(<span class="kw">int</span> x){<span class="kw">if</span>(parent[x]!=x) {
                parent[x]=<span class="fn">find</span>(parent[x]);
            }<span class="kw">return</span> parent[x];}
}</pre></div></div></div>

  <!-- ═══ BIT MANIPULATION ═══ -->
  <h2 class="section-heading" id="bit"><span class="section-icon">BM</span> Bit Manipulation</h2>

  <div class="problem-card"><div class="problem-card-header"><span class="problem-number">#136</span><h3 class="problem-heading" style="margin:0">Single Number</h3><span class="tag tag-green">Easy</span></div><div class="problem-card-body"><div class="technique-row"><span class="technique-label">🎯 Technique</span><span class="tag tag-blue">XOR Bit Property</span><span class="tag tag-teal">Pair Cancellation</span></div><div class="panel info"><span class="panel-icon">💡</span><div class="panel-content"><strong>Approach — XOR All Elements</strong>XOR property: a⊕a=0 and a⊕0=a. XOR all elements — duplicate pairs cancel to 0, leaving only the single number. O(1) space, no sorting, no hashing.</div></div><table class="complexity-table"><thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th>Complexity</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Time</td><td class="complexity-time">O(n)</td><td>One pass</td></tr><tr><td>Space</td><td class="complexity-space">O(1)</td><td>Single variable</td></tr></tbody></table><div class="code-block"><div class="code-header"><span class="code-lang">Java</span></div><pre><span class="kw">class</span> <span class="tp">Solution</span> {
    <span class="kw">public int</span> <span class="fn">singleNumber</span>(<span class="kw">int</span>[] nums){
        <span class="kw">int</span> res=<span class="nm">0</span>; <span class="kw">for</span>(<span class="kw">int</span> n:nums)res^=n; <span class="kw">return</span> res;
    }
}</pre></div></div></div>

  <div class="problem-card"><div class="problem-card-header"><span class="problem-number">#190</span><h3 class="problem-heading" style="margin:0">Reverse Bits</h3><span class="tag tag-green">Easy</span></div><div class="problem-card-body"><div class="technique-row"><span class="technique-label">🎯 Technique</span><span class="tag tag-blue">Bit Extraction &amp; Assembly</span><span class="tag tag-teal">32-bit Iteration</span></div><div class="panel info"><span class="panel-icon">💡</span><div class="panel-content"><strong>Approach — Extract and Reassemble Bits</strong>Loop 32 times. Each iteration: shift result left, OR in the current LSB of n (n&amp;1), shift n right. After 32 iterations, result holds the reversed bit pattern.</div></div><table class="complexity-table"><thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th>Complexity</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Time</td><td class="complexity-time">O(1)</td><td>Fixed 32 iterations always</td></tr><tr><td>Space</td><td class="complexity-space">O(1)</td><td>No extra storage</td></tr></tbody></table><div class="code-block"><div class="code-header"><span class="code-lang">Java</span></div><pre><span class="kw">public class</span> <span class="tp">Solution</span> {
    <span class="kw">public int</span> <span class="fn">reverseBits</span>(<span class="kw">int</span> n){
        <span class="kw">int</span> res=<span class="nm">0</span>;
        <span class="kw">for</span>(<span class="kw">int</span> i=<span class="nm">0</span>;i&lt;<span class="nm">32</span>;i++){res=(res&lt;&lt;<span class="nm">1</span>)|(n&amp;<span class="nm">1</span>);n&gt;&gt;=<span class="nm">1</span>;}
        <span class="kw">return</span> res;
    }
}</pre></div></div></div>

  <div class="problem-card"><div class="problem-card-header"><span class="problem-number">#191</span><h3 class="problem-heading" style="margin:0">Number of 1 Bits</h3><span class="tag tag-green">Easy</span></div><div class="problem-card-body"><div class="technique-row"><span class="technique-label">🎯 Technique</span><span class="tag tag-blue">Brian Kernighan's Algorithm</span><span class="tag tag-teal">Lowest Set Bit Removal</span></div><div class="panel info"><span class="panel-icon">💡</span><div class="panel-content"><strong>Approach — n &amp; (n-1) Trick</strong>n &amp; (n-1) clears the lowest set bit of n. Count how many times we can do this before n becomes 0. More efficient than checking every bit when the number of set bits is sparse.</div></div><table class="complexity-table"><thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th>Complexity</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Time</td><td class="complexity-time">O(k)</td><td>k = number of set bits</td></tr><tr><td>Space</td><td class="complexity-space">O(1)</td><td>One counter</td></tr></tbody></table><div class="code-block"><div class="code-header"><span class="code-lang">Java</span></div><pre><span class="kw">public class</span> <span class="tp">Solution</span> {
    <span class="kw">public int</span> <span class="fn">hammingWeight</span>(<span class="kw">int</span> n){
        <span class="kw">int</span> count=<span class="nm">0</span>;
        <span class="kw">while</span>(n!=<span class="nm">0</span>){n&amp;=(n-<span class="nm">1</span>);count++;}
        <span class="kw">return</span> count;
    }
}</pre></div></div></div>

  <div class="problem-card"><div class="problem-card-header"><span class="problem-number">#268</span><h3 class="problem-heading" style="margin:0">Missing Number</h3><span class="tag tag-green">Easy</span></div><div class="problem-card-body"><div class="technique-row"><span class="technique-label">🎯 Technique</span><span class="tag tag-blue">Gauss Sum Formula</span><span class="tag tag-teal">Math / XOR</span></div><div class="panel info"><span class="panel-icon">💡</span><div class="panel-content"><strong>Approach — Gauss Formula (Expected - Actual)</strong>Sum of 0..n = n*(n+1)/2. Subtract the actual array sum. The difference is the missing number. Alternatively use XOR of all indices and elements — pairs cancel, leaving the missing value.</div></div><table class="complexity-table"><thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th>Complexity</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Time</td><td class="complexity-time">O(n)</td><td>One pass</td></tr><tr><td>Space</td><td class="complexity-space">O(1)</td><td>Two variables</td></tr></tbody></table><div class="code-block"><div class="code-header"><span class="code-lang">Java</span></div><pre><span class="kw">class</span> <span class="tp">Solution</span> {
    <span class="kw">public int</span> <span class="fn">missingNumber</span>(<span class="kw">int</span>[] nums){
        <span class="kw">int</span> n=nums.length, sum=<span class="nm">0</span>;
        <span class="kw">for</span>(<span class="kw">int</span> x:nums)sum+=x;
        <span class="kw">return</span> n*(n+<span class="nm">1</span>)/<span class="nm">2</span>-sum;
    }
}</pre></div></div></div>

  <!-- ═══ PATTERN CHEATSHEET ═══ -->
  <h2 class="section-heading" id="patterns"><span class="section-icon">📋</span> Pattern Cheatsheet</h2>
  <div class="panel tip"><span class="panel-icon">✅</span><div class="panel-content"><strong>Quick Reference</strong> — Use this table to identify which technique to reach for based on the problem signal words.</div></div>

  <table class="tips-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Pattern</th><th>Signal Words</th><th>Key Idea</th><th>Typical Complexity</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Two Pointers</td><td>sorted array, pairs summing to target, palindrome, remove duplicates</td><td>Move pointers toward each other or at different speeds to reduce O(n²) → O(n)</td><td>O(n) time, O(1) space</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Sliding Window</td><td>subarray/substring with constraint, min/max window, frequency</td><td>Expand right until valid, shrink left to minimize/maximize. Maintain a running state</td><td>O(n) time, O(k) space</td></tr>
      <tr><td>HashMap / HashSet</td><td>count frequencies, find complement, detect duplicate, group by key</td><td>Trade O(n) space for O(1) average lookup to reduce O(n²) to O(n)</td><td>O(n) time, O(n) space</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Monotonic Stack</td><td>next greater/smaller, daily temperatures, largest rectangle</td><td>Maintain stack in order. Pop when invariant violated — popped elements have found their answer</td><td>O(n) time, O(n) space</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Binary Search</td><td>sorted array, find position, minimise/maximise satisfying condition, rotated</td><td>Eliminate half the search space each step. Also apply on answer space, not just input</td><td>O(log n) time, O(1) space</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Backtracking</td><td>all combinations/permutations/subsets, constraint satisfaction, N-Queens, Sudoku</td><td>Build incrementally. Prune invalid branches early. Undo choice (restore state) after each branch</td><td>Exponential worst case; pruning critical</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Dynamic Programming</td><td>count ways, min/max value, can we achieve X, overlapping subproblems</td><td>Define state → write recurrence → add base cases → optimize space if possible</td><td>Varies; typically O(n) to O(n²)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>BFS</td><td>shortest path (unweighted), level order, spread from multiple sources, minimum steps</td><td>Explore level by level. Use queue. Multi-source: seed all sources at once</td><td>O(V+E) time, O(V) space</td></tr>
      <tr><td>DFS</td><td>explore all paths, cycle detection, connected components, topological sort</td><td>Go deep first. Use recursion or explicit stack. 3-color for cycle detection</td><td>O(V+E) time, O(V) space</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Union-Find (DSU)</td><td>connected components, dynamic connectivity, Kruskal's MST</td><td>Path compression + union by rank → nearly O(1) per operation. Count components by tracking merges</td><td>O(α(n)) per op ≈ O(1)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Fast &amp; Slow Pointers</td><td>cycle detection, find middle, palindrome in list</td><td>Slow moves 1 step, fast moves 2. They meet in cycles; slow finds midpoint</td><td>O(n) time, O(1) space</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Expand Around Center</td><td>palindromic substring, longest palindrome</td><td>Try expanding from each center (char and gap). Covers odd and even lengths without DP array</td><td>O(n²) time, O(1) space</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Prefix Sum / Product</td><td>range sum queries, product except self, subarray sum equals k</td><td>Precompute cumulative values so any range query is O(1) rather than O(n)</td><td>O(n) preprocessing, O(1) query</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Bit Manipulation</td><td>find unique number, count bits, missing number, power of 2</td><td>XOR pairs cancel (a⊕a=0). n&amp;(n-1) clears lowest bit. n*(n+1)/2 gives Gauss sum</td><td>O(1) or O(n) depending on problem</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

